{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"527f28fb-3247-4da2-a857-be1385d62c94","content":"For a .NET Web API, use the `dotnet new webapi` template. Authentication options include:\n\n| Option | Flag |\n|---|---|\n| None (default) | `--auth None` |\n| Individual accounts | `--auth Individual` |\n| Azure AD (Entra ID) | `--auth SingleOrg` |\n| Azure AD B2C | `--auth IndividualB2C` |\n| Multi-org Azure AD | `--auth MultiOrg` |\n| Windows auth | `--auth Windows` |\n\n**Example:**\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi --auth Individual\n```\n\nAdd `--use-minimal-apis` for minimal API style, or `--use-controllers` for controller-based. Run `dotnet new webapi --help` for the full list of options.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"90b47cd8-a2f1-4957-82a7-6050a2637107","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":273,"requestId":"403A:2AE020:43FC36:4F88B3:69F0048D"},"id":"eb7cf96c-6d8f-461a-990d-d3a118780a7b","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:51:33.802Z","parentId":"6c9dc65d-479d-4167-b9ae-56934fe4a2f0"}
